    0 defmodule Klepsidra.Accounts.User do
    1 @moduledoc """
    2 Define a schema for the `User` entity, recording authorised system users,
    3 for authorisation, ownership, auditing and logging purposes.
    4 """
    5
    6 use Ecto.Schema
    7 import Ecto.Changeset
    8
    9 @primary_key {:id, Ecto.UUID, autogenerate: true}
    10 @foreign_key_type Ecto.UUID
    11
    12 @type t :: %__MODULE__{
    13 user_name: String.t(),
    14 login_email: String.t(),
    15 password_hash: String.t(),
    16 description: String.t(),
    17 frozen: boolean(),
    18 active: boolean()
    19 }
    20 243 schema "users" do
    21 field :user_name, :string
    22 field :login_email, :string
    23 field :password_hash, :string
    24 field :description, :string
    25 field :frozen, :boolean, default: false
    26 field :active, :boolean, default: true
    27
    28 timestamps()
    29 end
    30
    31 @doc false
    32 def changeset(user, attrs) do
    33 user
    34 |> cast(attrs, [:user_name, :login_email, :password_hash, :frozen, :active])
    35 |> validate_required([:user_name, :login_email, :password_hash])
    36 |> unique_constraint(:user_name,
    37 name: :users_user_name_index,
    38 message: "This user name is taken"
    39 )
    40 26 |> unique_constraint(:login_email,
    41 name: :users_login_email_index,
    42 message: "This login email has already been registered"
    43 )
    44 end
    45 end

    0 defmodule Klepsidra.Application do
    1 # See https://hexdocs.pm/elixir/Application.html
    2 # for more information on OTP Applications
    3 @moduledoc false
    4
    5 use Application
    6
    7 @impl true
    8 def start(_type, _args) do
    9 1 children = [
    10 # Start the Telemetry supervisor
    11 KlepsidraWeb.Telemetry,
    12 # Start the Ecto repository
    13 Klepsidra.Repo,
    14 # Start the PubSub system
    15 {Phoenix.PubSub, name: Klepsidra.PubSub},
    16 # Start Finch
    17 {Finch, name: Klepsidra.Finch},
    18 # Start the Endpoint (http/https)
    19 KlepsidraWeb.Endpoint
    20 # Start a worker by calling: Klepsidra.Worker.start_link(arg)
    21 # {Klepsidra.Worker, arg}
    22 ]
    23
    24 # See https://hexdocs.pm/elixir/Supervisor.html
    25 # for other strategies and supported options
    26 1 opts = [strategy: :one_for_one, name: Klepsidra.Supervisor]
    27 1 Supervisor.start_link(children, opts)
    28 end
    29
    30 # Tell Phoenix to update the endpoint configuration
    31 # whenever the application is updated.
    32 @impl true
    33 def config_change(changed, _new, removed) do
    34 0 KlepsidraWeb.Endpoint.config_change(changed, removed)
    35 :ok
    36 end
    37 end

    0 defmodule Klepsidra.Categorisation do
    1 @moduledoc """
    2 The Categorisation context provides a way to categorise entities within the
    3 application.
    4
    5 A general-purpose _tagging_ module provides a record of all tags used for various entities.
    6 Presently, tagging is only used in activity timers so that users can simply categorise
    7 their timed activities, to help filter activities by category, to search for timers, and to
    8 make it easier to collate timers with client invoicing in mind.
    9
    10 Tagging activity timers requires a many-to-many relationship between timers and
    11 tags, which is recorded in the `timer_tags` table.
    12 """
    13
    14 import Ecto.Query, warn: false
    15 alias Klepsidra.Repo
    16
    17 alias Klepsidra.Categorisation.Tag
    18 alias Klepsidra.Categorisation.TimerTags
    19

    21 Returns the list of tags.
    22
    23 ## Examples
    24
    25 iex> list_tags()
    26 [%Tag{}, ...]
    27
    28 """
    29 def list_tags do
    30 9 Tag |> order_by(asc: fragment("name COLLATE NOCASE")) |> Repo.all()
    31 end
    32
    33 @doc """
    34 Gets a single tag.
    35
    36 Raises `Ecto.NoResultsError` if the Tag does not exist.
    37
    38 ## Examples
    39
    40 iex> get_tag!(123)
    41 %Tag{}
    42
    43 iex> get_tag!(456)
    44 ** (Ecto.NoResultsError)
    45
    46 """
    47 11 def get_tag!(id), do: Repo.get!(Tag, id)
    48
    49 @doc """
    50 Creates a tag.
    51
    52 ## Examples
    53
    54 iex> create_tag(%{field: value})
    55 {:ok, %Tag{}}

    57 iex> create_tag(%{field: bad_value})

    66
    67 @doc """

    170 @doc """
    171 Simple search for tags defined in the system, performing a prefix filter only.
    172
    173 This search takes in the `search_phrase`, and after converting it to lowercase,
    174 compares it against a list of similarly lowercased tag names (`name` field), from the
    175 database. The comparison checks filters all tags that start with the normalised
    176 search phrase.
    177
    178 ## Examples
    179
    180 iex> search_tags_by_name_prefix("hello")
    181 [%Tag{}, ...]
    182 """
    183 @spec search_tags_by_name_prefix(String.t()) :: [Tag.t(), ...]
    184 def search_tags_by_name_prefix(search_phrase) do
    185 0 search_phrase = String.downcase(search_phrase)
    186
    187 Klepsidra.Categorisation.list_tags()
    188 0 |> Enum.filter(fn %{name: name} ->
    189 0 String.starts_with?(String.downcase(name), search_phrase)
    190 end)
    191 end

    2 Defines additional time units encountered in the commercial world.
    3
    4 Businesses record their time units in a range of time units, or billing increments,
    5 based on standard time primitives such as minutes and hours. Building on `Cldr.Units`,
    6 any desired time units must be defined here before they can be used in an application,
    7 since they must be compiled prior to use.

    18

    23 end

    36 [JournalEntry.t(), ...]
    37 def preload_journal_entry_type(journal_entries) when is_list(journal_entries) do
    38 0 Repo.preload(journal_entries, :entry_type)

    0 defmodule Klepsidra.Journals.JournalEntry do
    1 @moduledoc """
    2 Defines the `journal_entries` schema needed to record a generic set of journaling
    3 needs, from the deeply personal, to commercial.
    4 """
    5
    6 use Ecto.Schema
    7 import Ecto.Changeset
    8
    9 @primary_key {:id, Ecto.UUID, autogenerate: true}
    10 @foreign_key_type Ecto.UUID
    11
    12 @type t :: %__MODULE__{
    13 journal_for: String.t(),
    14 entry_text_markdown: String.t(),
    15 entry_text_html: String.t(),
    16 highlights: String.t(),

    454 def truncate(text, opts) do
    455 0 max_length = opts[:max_length] || 59
    456 0 omission = opts[:omission] || "..."
    457
    458 0 cond do
    459 not String.valid?(text) ->
    460 0 text
    461
    462 0 String.length(text) < max_length ->
    463 0 text
    464
    465 0 true ->
    466 0 length_with_omission = max_length - String.length(omission)
    467
    468 0 "#{String.slice(text, 0, length_with_omission)}#{omission}"
    469 end
    470 end

    479 smartypants: true
    480 )
    481 9 |> HtmlSanitizeEx.html5()
    482 end

    0 defmodule Klepsidra.TimeTracking.ActivityType do
    1 @moduledoc """
    2 Defines a schema for the `ActivityType` entity, used to set activity types on timers.
    3
    4 Activity types are a way to preload billing defaults, to help calculate
    5 billing amounts at time of invoicing.
    6 """
    7
    8 use Ecto.Schema
    9 import Ecto.Changeset
    10
    11 @primary_key {:id, Ecto.UUID, autogenerate: true}
    12 @foreign_key_type Ecto.UUID
    13
    14 @type t :: %__MODULE__{
    15 name: String.t(),
    16 billing_rate: number(),
    17 active: boolean()
    18 }
    19 277 schema "activity_types" do
    20 field :name, :string
    21 field :billing_rate, :decimal
    22 field :active, :boolean, default: true
    23
    24 timestamps()
    25 end
    26
    27 @doc false
    28 def changeset(activity_type, attrs) do
    29 activity_type
    30 |> cast(attrs, [:name, :billing_rate, :active])
    31 |> validate_required([:name], message: "Enter an activity type name")
    32 |> unique_constraint(:name, message: "An activity type with this name already exists")
    33 |> validate_required([:billing_rate], message: "The hourly billing rate must be a number")
    34 26 |> validate_number(:billing_rate,
    35 greater_than_or_equal_to: 0,
    36 message: "The billing rate must be zero or greater"
    37 )
    38 end
    39
    40 @doc """
    41 Used across live components to populate select options with activity types.
    42 """
    43 @spec populate_activity_types_list() :: [Klepsidra.TimeTracking.ActivityType.t(), ...]

    101 start_timestamp :: atom,
    102 end_timestamp :: atom,
    103 opts :: Keyword.t()

    105 def validate_timestamps_and_chronology(changeset, start_timestamp, end_timestamp, opts \\ []) do
    106 19 _message = Keyword.get(opts, :message, "Timestamps are not in valid order")
    107 19 start_stamp = get_field(changeset, start_timestamp, "")
    108
    109 19 parsed_start_stamp =
    110 case parse_html_datetime(start_stamp) do
    111 17 {:ok, start_datetime_stamp} -> start_datetime_stamp
    112 2 _ -> nil
    113 end
    114
    115 19 end_stamp = get_field(changeset, end_timestamp, "") || ""
    116
    117 19 parsed_end_stamp =
    118 case parse_html_datetime(end_stamp) do
    119 16 {:ok, end_datetime_stamp} -> end_datetime_stamp
    120 3 _ -> nil
    121 end
    122
    123 19 with {:is_valid, true} <- {:is_valid, changeset.valid?},
    124 16 {:nonempty_start_stamp, true} <-
    125 {:nonempty_start_stamp, start_stamp != ""},
    126 16 {:valid_start_stamp, true} <-
    127 16 {:valid_start_stamp, is_struct(parsed_start_stamp, NaiveDateTime)},
    128 16 {:nonempty_end_stamp, true} <- {:nonempty_end_stamp, end_stamp != ""},
    129 16 {:valid_end_stamp, true} <-
    130 16 {:valid_end_stamp, is_struct(parsed_end_stamp, NaiveDateTime)},
    131 16 {:chronological_order, true} <-
    132 {:chronological_order, NaiveDateTime.before?(parsed_start_stamp, parsed_end_stamp)},
    133 16 {:reasonable_duration_check, true} <-
    134 {:reasonable_duration_check,
    135 NaiveDateTime.before?(
    136 parsed_end_stamp,
    137 NaiveDateTime.add(parsed_start_stamp, 24, :hour)
    138 )} do
    139 16 changeset
    140 else
    141 {:is_valid, false} ->
    142 3 changeset
    143
    144 {:nonempty_start_stamp, false} ->
    145 0 add_error(changeset, :end_stamp, "You must provide a start time and date")
    146
    147 {:valid_start_stamp, false} ->
    148 0 add_error(changeset, :end_stamp, "The start time and date is not valid")
    149
    150 {:nonempty_end_stamp, false} ->
    151 0 changeset
    152
    153 {:valid_end_stamp, false} ->
    154 0 add_error(changeset, :end_stamp, "The end time and date is not valid")
    155
    156 {:chronological_order, false} ->
    157 0 add_error(changeset, :end_stamp, "The end time must follow the start time")
    158
    159 {:reasonable_duration_check, false} ->
    160 0 add_error(changeset, :end_stamp, "The timed activity cannot be longer than one day")

    188 @doc """
    189 Calculates the time elapsed between start and end timestamps.
    190
    191 The time unit can be passed in as the optional `unit` argument. If it is omitted,
    192 minutes are used as the default time unit.
    193
    194 In calculating the time duration, the difference between the two timestamps is
    195 always incremented by one. This ensures that if the timer were simply started
    196 and immediately stopped, it would still register the use of one unit of time.
    197
    198 If the start and end `datetime` stamps are empty strings, or nil values, returns
    199 zero duration to reduce the number of error conditions.
    200
    201 ## Examples
    202
    203 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.calculate_timer_duration("2024-02-28 12:34", "2024-02-28 13:45")
    204 72
    205
    206 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.calculate_timer_duration("2024-02-28 12:34", "2024-02-28 13:45", :minute)
    207 72
    208

    210 4261
    211
    212 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.calculate_timer_duration("2024-02-28 12:34", "2024-02-28 13:45", :hour)
    213 2
    214
    215 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.calculate_timer_duration("2024-02-28 12:34", "2024-02-28 13:34", :hour)
    216 2
    217
    218 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.calculate_timer_duration("2024-02-28 12:34", "2024-02-28 13:33", :hour)
    219 1
    220
    221 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.calculate_timer_duration(~N[2024-06-06 23:40:31], ~N[2024-06-07 01:23:45])
    222 104
    223
    224 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.calculate_timer_duration(~N[2024-06-06 23:40:31], ~N[2024-06-07 01:23:45], :minute)
    225 104
    226
    227 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.calculate_timer_duration(~N[2024-06-06 23:40:31], ~N[2024-06-07 01:23:45], :second)
    228 6195
    229
    230 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.calculate_timer_duration(~N[2024-06-06 23:40:31], ~N[2024-06-07 01:23:45], :hour)
    231 2
    232 """
    233 @spec calculate_timer_duration(String.t(), String.t(), atom()) :: integer()
    234 @spec calculate_timer_duration(NaiveDateTime.t(), NaiveDateTime.t(), atom()) :: integer()
    235 2 def calculate_timer_duration(start_timestamp, end_timestamp, unit \\ :minute)
    236

    249 def calculate_timer_duration(start_timestamp, end_timestamp, unit)
    250 when is_struct(start_timestamp, NaiveDateTime) and
    251 is_struct(
    252 end_timestamp,
    253 NaiveDateTime
    254 ) and is_atom(unit) do
    255 12 with {:end_follows_start, true} <-
    256 {:end_follows_start, NaiveDateTime.after?(end_timestamp, start_timestamp)},
    257 12 {:uses_time_unit_primitive, true} <-
    258 12 {:uses_time_unit_primitive, unit in [:second, :minute, :hour, :day]} do
    259 12 NaiveDateTime.diff(end_timestamp, start_timestamp, unit) + 1
    260 else
    261 0 {:end_follows_start, false} ->
    262 0
    263
    264 {:uses_time_unit_primitive, false} ->
    265 (NaiveDateTime.diff(end_timestamp, start_timestamp, :minute) + 1)
    266 |> Cldr.Unit.new!(:minute)
    267 |> Klepsidra.Cldr.Unit.convert!(unit)
    268 |> Map.get(:value)
    269 |> Decimal.round(0, :up)

    311 @doc """
    312 Parses HTML `datetime-local` strings into `NativeDateTime` structure.
    313
    314 Datetime strings coming from HTML, from `datetime-local` type fields,
    315 are not conformant to the extended date and time of day ISO 8601:2019 standard format.
    316 Specifically, they are encoded as "YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm", and are generally (but not always)
    317 passed without a seconds component. `NativeDateTime` cannot parse this, returning an
    318 error.
    319
    320 Using the Timex library's `parse/2` function, parse datetime strings into an ISO
    321 conforming `NativeDateTime` structure, returning a result tuple:
    322
    323 `{:ok, ~N[...]}` on success, or {:error, reason} upon failure.
    324
    325 It is possible to receive a datetime with date and time components separated by either
    326 a letter "t" or a single space (" "), binary pattern matching will determine which is
    327 received in the `datetime_string` argument.
    328
    329 An error is returned if the datetime string cannot be parsed as a valid date and time,
    330 and also if the string doesn't match the expected pattern.
    331
    332 ## Examples
    333
    334 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.parse_html_datetime("1970-01-01T11:15")
    335 {:ok, ~N[1970-01-01 11:15:00]}
    336
    337 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.parse_html_datetime("1970-01-01T11:15:39")
    338 {:ok, ~N[1970-01-01 11:15:39]}
    339
    340 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.parse_html_datetime("1970-01-01 11:15")
    341 {:ok, ~N[1970-01-01 11:15:00]}
    342
    343 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.parse_html_datetime("1970-01-01 11:15:59")
    344 {:ok, ~N[1970-01-01 11:15:59]}
    345
    346 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.parse_html_datetime("1970-02-29T11:15")
    347 {:error, :invalid_date}
    348
    349 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.parse_html_datetime("")
    350 {:error, "Invalid argument passed as timestamp"}
    351
    352 iex> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.Timer.parse_html_datetime(nil)
    353 {:error, "Invalid argument passed as timestamp"}
    354 """
    355 @spec parse_html_datetime(String.t()) :: {:ok, NaiveDateTime.t()} | {:error, String.t()}
    356 def parse_html_datetime(
    357 <<_year::binary-size(4), "-", _month::binary-size(2), "-", _day::binary-size(2), "T",
    358 _hour::binary-size(2), ":", _minute::binary-size(2)>> = datetime_string
    359 )
    360 when is_bitstring(datetime_string) do
    361 4 Timex.parse(datetime_string, "{YYYY}-{0M}-{0D}T{0h24}:{0m}")
    362 end

    449 @doc """

    227 Renders an input with label and error messages.

    229 A `%Phoenix.HTML.Form{}` and field name may be passed to the input
    230 to build input names and error messages, or all the attributes and
    231 errors may be passed explicitly.

    233 ## Examples
    234

    237 """
    238 attr :id, :any, default: nil
    239 attr :name, :any
    240 attr :label, :string, default: nil
    241 attr :value, :any
    242
    243 attr :type, :string,
    244 default: "text",
    245 values: ~w(checkbox color date datetime-local email file hidden month number password
    246 range radio search select tel text textarea time url week)
    247
    248 attr :field, Phoenix.HTML.FormField,
    249 doc: "a form field struct retrieved from the form, for example: @form[:email]"
    250
    251 attr :errors, :list, default: []
    252 attr :checked, :boolean, doc: "the checked flag for checkbox inputs"
    253 attr :prompt, :string, default: nil, doc: "the prompt for select inputs"
    254 attr :options, :list, doc: "the options to pass to Phoenix.HTML.Form.options_for_select/2"
    255 attr :multiple, :boolean, default: false, doc: "the multiple flag for select inputs"

    259 pattern placeholder readonly required rows size step)

    263 def input(%{field: %Phoenix.HTML.FormField{} = field} = assigns) do
    264 assigns
    265 132 |> assign(field: nil, id: assigns.id || field.id)
    266 132 |> assign(:errors, Enum.map(field.errors, &translate_error(&1)))
    267 132 |> assign_new(:name, fn -> if assigns.multiple, do: field.name <> "[]", else: field.name end)
    268 132 |> assign_new(:value, fn -> field.value end)
    269 132 |> input()
    270 end

    571 ## JS Commands
    572
    573 def show(js \\ %JS{}, selector) do
    574 19 JS.show(js,
    575 to: selector,
    576 transition:
    577 {"transition-all transform ease-out duration-300",
    578 "opacity-0 translate-y-4 sm:translate-y-0 sm:scale-95",
    579 "opacity-100 translate-y-0 sm:scale-100"}
    580 )
    581 end
    582
    583 def hide(js \\ %JS{}, selector) do
    584 77 JS.hide(js,
    585 to: selector,
    586 time: 200,
    587 transition:
    588 {"transition-all transform ease-in duration-200",
    589 "opacity-100 translate-y-0 sm:scale-100",
    590 "opacity-0 translate-y-4 sm:translate-y-0 sm:scale-95"}
    591 )
    592 end
    593
    594 def show_modal(js \\ %JS{}, id) when is_binary(id) do
    595 js
    596 19 |> JS.show(to: "##{id}")
    597 |> JS.show(
    598 19 to: "##{id}-bg",
    599 transition: {"transition-all transform ease-out duration-300", "opacity-0", "opacity-100"}
    600 )
    601 19 |> show("##{id}-container")
    602 |> JS.add_class("overflow-hidden", to: "body")
    603 19 |> JS.focus_first(to: "##{id}-content")
    604 end
    605
    606 def hide_modal(js \\ %JS{}, id) do
    607 js
    608 |> JS.hide(
    609 19 to: "##{id}-bg",
    610 transition: {"transition-all transform ease-in duration-200", "opacity-100", "opacity-0"}
    611 )
    612 19 |> hide("##{id}-container")
    613 19 |> JS.hide(to: "##{id}", transition: {"block", "block", "hidden"})
    614 |> JS.remove_class("overflow-hidden", to: "body")
    615 19 |> JS.pop_focus()
    616 end
    617
    618 @doc """
    619 Translates an error message using gettext.
    620 """
    621 def translate_error({msg, opts}) do
    622 # When using gettext, we typically pass the strings we want
    623 # to translate as a static argument:
    624 #
    625 # # Translate the number of files with plural rules
    626 # dngettext("errors", "1 file", "%{count} files", count)
    627 #
    628 # However the error messages in our forms and APIs are generated
    629 # dynamically, so we need to translate them by calling Gettext
    630 # with our gettext backend as first argument. Translations are
    631 # available in the errors.po file (as we use the "errors" domain).
    632 29 if count = opts[:count] do
    633 0 Gettext.dngettext(KlepsidraWeb.Gettext, "errors", msg, msg, count, opts)
    634 else
    635 29 Gettext.dgettext(KlepsidraWeb.Gettext, "errors", msg, opts)
    636 end
    637 end
    638
    639 @doc """
    640 Translates the errors for a field from a keyword list of errors.
    641 """
    642 def translate_errors(errors, field) when is_list(errors) do
    643 0 for {^field, {msg, opts}} <- errors, do: translate_error({msg, opts})
    644 end
    645 end

    0 defmodule KlepsidraWeb.Endpoint do
    1 @moduledoc false
    2
    3 use Phoenix.Endpoint, otp_app: :klepsidra
    4
    5 # The session will be stored in the cookie and signed,
    6 # this means its contents can be read but not tampered with.
    7 # Set :encryption_salt if you would also like to encrypt it.
    8 @session_options [
    9 store: :cookie,
    10 key: "_klepsidra_key",
    11 signing_salt: "tTGt4N0Z",
    12 same_site: "Lax"
    13 ]
    14
    15 socket "/live", Phoenix.LiveView.Socket, websocket: [connect_info: [session: @session_options]]
    16
    17 # Serve at "/" the static files from "priv/static" directory.
    18 #
    19 # You should set gzip to true if you are running phx.digest
    20 # when deploying your static files in production.
    21 plug Plug.Static,
    22 at: "/",
    23 from: :klepsidra,
    24 gzip: false,
    25 only: KlepsidraWeb.static_paths()
    26
    27 # Code reloading can be explicitly enabled under the
    28 # :code_reloader configuration of your endpoint.
    29 if code_reloading? do
    30 socket "/phoenix/live_reload/socket", Phoenix.LiveReloader.Socket

    0 defmodule KlepsidraWeb.CSP do
    1 @moduledoc """
    2 Module that includes Plug and LiveView helpers to handle Content Security
    3 Policy header.
    4
    5 For inline `<style>` and `<script>` tags, nonce should be used. When the REST
    6 request is processed a nonce is added to the process dictionary. This ensures
    7 the nonce stays the same throughout the call, as the nonce in the tags must
    8 match the nonce in the header.
    9
    10 To allow for inline `<style>` and/or `<script>` tag you must set a `'nonce'`
    11 source.
    12
    13 ## Set up
    14
    15 To set up MyAppWeb.CSP in your app you must:
    16
    17 ### 1) Configure `lib/my_app_web.ex`
    18
    19 Ensure you import the helpers in `MyAppWeb`.
    20
    21 def router do
    22 quote do
    23 use Phoenix.Router, helpers: false
    24
    25 # Import common connection and controller functions to use in pipelines
    26 import Plug.Conn
    27 import Phoenix.Controller
    28 import Phoenix.LiveView.Router
    29
    30 import MyAppWeb.CSP, only: [put_content_security_policy: 2]
    31 end
    32 end
    33
    34 # ...
    35
    36 def html do
    37 quote do
    38 use Phoenix.Component
    39
    40 import MyAppWeb.CldrHelpers
    41
    42 # Import convenience functions from controllers
    43 import Phoenix.Controller,
    44 only: [get_csrf_token: 0, view_module: 1, view_template: 1]
    45
    46 import MyAppWeb.CSP,
    47 only: [get_csp_nonce: 0]
    48
    49 # Include general helpers for rendering HTML
    50 unquote(html_helpers())
    51 end
    52 end
    53
    54 # ...
    55
    56 def live_view do
    57 quote do
    58 use Phoenix.LiveView,
    59 layout: {MyAppWeb.Layouts, :app}
    60
    61 on_mount MyAppWeb.CSP
    62
    63 unquote(html_helpers())
    64 end
    65 end
    66
    67 ### 2) Add nonce metatag to the HTML document
    68
    69 Add the following metatag head to
    70 `lib/my_app_web/components/layouts/root.html.heex`.
    71
    72 <meta name="csp-nonce" content={get_csp_nonce()} />
    73
    74 ### 3) Pass the CSP nonce to the LiveView socket
    75
    76 Ensure you pass on the CSP nonce to the LiveView socket in
    77 `assets/js/app.js`.
    78
    79 let csrfToken = document.querySelector("meta[name='csrf-token']").getAttribute("content");
    80 let cspNonce = document.querySelector("meta[name='csp-nonce']").getAttribute("content")
    81 let liveSocket = new LiveSocket("/live", Socket, {
    82 longPollFallbackMs: 2500,
    83 params: { _csrf_token: csrfToken, _csp_nonce: cspNonce }
    84 })
    85
    86 ## Usage
    87
    88 If you got inline `<style>` or script tags you must set the nonce attribute:
    89
    90 <style nonce={get_csp_nonce()}>
    91 // ...
    92 </style>
    93 """
    94 require Logger
    95
    96 import Plug.Conn
    97
    98 @doc """
    99 Sets a content security policy header.
    100
    101 By default the policy is `default-src 'self'`. `'nonce'` source will be
    102 expanded with an auto-generated nonce that is persisted in the process
    103 dictionary.
    104
    105 The options can be a function or a keyword list. Sources can be a binary
    106 or list of binaries. Duplicate directives will be merged together.
    107
    108 ## Example
    109
    110 plug :put_content_security_policy,
    111 img_src: "'self' data:`,
    112 style_src: "'self' 'nonce'"
    113
    114 plug :put_content_security_policy,
    115 img_src: [
    116 "'self'",
    117 "data:"
    118 ]
    119
    120 plug :put_content_security_policy, &MyAppWeb.CSPPolicy.opts/1
    121 """
    122 def put_content_security_policy(conn, fun) when is_function(fun, 1) do
    123 0 put_content_security_policy(conn, fun.(conn))
    124 end
    125
    126 def put_content_security_policy(conn, opts) when is_list(opts) do
    127 39 csp =
    128 opts
    129 |> Keyword.has_key?(:default_src)
    130 |> case do
    131 39 false -> [default_src: "'self'"] ++ opts
    132 0 true -> opts
    133 end
    134 |> Enum.reduce([], fn {name, sources}, acc ->
    135 117 sources = List.wrap(sources)
    136
    137 117 Keyword.update(acc, name, sources, &(&1 ++ sources))
    138 end)
    139 |> Enum.reduce("", fn {name, sources}, acc ->
    140 117 name = String.replace(to_string(name), "_", "-")
    141
    142 117 sources =
    143 sources
    144 |> Enum.uniq()
    145 |> Enum.join(" ")
    146 117 |> String.replace("'nonce'", "'nonce-#{get_csp_nonce()}'")
    147
    148 117 "#{acc}#{name} #{sources};"
    149 end)
    150
    151 39 put_resp_header(conn, "content-security-policy", csp)
    152 end
    153
    154 @doc """
    155 Gets the CSP nonce.
    156
    157 Generates a nonce and stores it in the process dictionary if one does not exist.
    158 """
    159 def get_csp_nonce do
    160 117 if nonce = Process.get(:plug_csp_nonce) do
    161 78 nonce
    162 else
    163 39 nonce = csp_nonce()
    164 39 Process.put(:plug_csp_nonce, nonce)
    165 39 nonce
    166 end
    167 end
    168
    169 defp csp_nonce do
    170 24
    171 |> :crypto.strong_rand_bytes()
    172 39 |> Base.encode64(padding: false)
    173 end
    174
    175 @doc """
    176 Loads the CSP nonce into the LiveView process.
    177 """
    178 def on_mount(
    179 :default,
    180 _params,
    181 _session,
    182 %{private: %{connect_params: %{"_csp_nonce" => nonce}}} = socket
    183 ) do
    184 0 Process.put(:plug_csp_nonce, nonce)
    185
    186 {:cont, socket}
    187 end
    188
    189 def on_mount(:default, _params, _session, socket) do
    190 0 unless Process.get(:plug_csp_nonce) do
    191 0 Logger.debug("""
    192 LiveView session was misconfigured.
    193
    194 1) Ensure the `put_content_security_policy` plug is in your router pipeline:
    195
    196 plug :put_content_security_policy
    197
    198 2) Define the CSRF meta tag inside the `<head>` tag in your layout:
    199
    200 <meta name="csp-nonce" content={MyAppWeb.CSP.get_csp_nonce()} />
    201
    202 3) Pass it forward in your app.js:
    203
    204 let csrfToken = document.querySelector("meta[name='csp-nonce']").getAttribute("content");
    205 let liveSocket = new LiveSocket("/live", Socket, {params: {_csp_nonce: cspNonce}});
    206 """)
    207 end
    208
    209 {:cont, socket}
    210 end
    211 end

    33 1 defp page_title(:edit), do: "Edit Project"
    34
    35 defp get_aggregate_duration_for_project(project_id) do
    36 project_id
    37 |> Klepsidra.TimeTracking.get_closed_timer_durations_for_project()
    38 |> Timer.convert_durations_to_base_time_unit()
    39 |> Timer.sum_base_unit_durations()
    40 6 |> format_aggregate_duration_for_project()
    41 end
    42
    43 defp format_aggregate_duration_for_project(base_unit_duration) do
    44 6 %{
    45 base_unit_duration: base_unit_duration,
    46 duration_in_hours:
    47 base_unit_duration
    48 |> Unit.convert!(:hour)
    49 6 |> then(fn i -> Cldr.Unit.round(i, 1) end)
    50 |> Unit.to_string!(),
    51 human_readable_duration:
    52 Timer.format_human_readable_duration(base_unit_duration,
    53 unit_list: [
    54 :day,
    55 :hour_increment
    56 ],
    57 return_if_short_duration: false
    58 )
    59 }
    60 end

    0 defmodule KlepsidraWeb.ConnCase do
    1 @moduledoc """
    2 This module defines the test case to be used by
    3 tests that require setting up a connection.
    4
    5 Such tests rely on `Phoenix.ConnTest` and also
    6 import other functionality to make it easier
    7 to build common data structures and query the data layer.
    8
    9 Finally, if the test case interacts with the database,
    10 we enable the SQL sandbox, so changes done to the database
    11 are reverted at the end of every test. If you are using
    12 PostgreSQL, you can even run database tests asynchronously
    13 by setting `use KlepsidraWeb.ConnCase, async: true`, although
    14 this option is not recommended for other databases.
    15 """
    16
    17 use ExUnit.CaseTemplate
    18
    19 10 using do
    20 quote do
    21 # The default endpoint for testing
    22 @endpoint KlepsidraWeb.Endpoint
    23
    24 use KlepsidraWeb, :verified_routes
    25
    26 # Import conveniences for testing with connections
    27 import Plug.Conn
    28 import Phoenix.ConnTest
    29 import KlepsidraWeb.ConnCase
    30 end
    31 end
    32
    33 setup tags do
    34 43 Klepsidra.DataCase.setup_sandbox(tags)
    35 {:ok, conn: Phoenix.ConnTest.build_conn()}
    36 end
    37 end

    0 defmodule Klepsidra.DataCase do
    1 @moduledoc """

    3 access to the application's data layer.

    5 You may define functions here to be used as helpers in
    6 your tests.
    7
    8 Finally, if the test case interacts with the database,
    9 we enable the SQL sandbox, so changes done to the database
    10 are reverted at the end of every test. If you are using
    11 PostgreSQL, you can even run database tests asynchronously
    12 by setting `use Klepsidra.DataCase, async: true`, although
    13 this option is not recommended for other databases.
    14 """
    15
    16 use ExUnit.CaseTemplate
    17
    18 6 using do
    19 quote do
    20 alias Klepsidra.Repo

    36 """
    37 def setup_sandbox(tags) do
    38 145 pid = Ecto.Adapters.SQL.Sandbox.start_owner!(Klepsidra.Repo, shared: not tags[:async])
    39 145 on_exit(fn -> Ecto.Adapters.SQL.Sandbox.stop_owner(pid) end)
    40 end
    41
    42 @doc """
    43 A helper that transforms changeset errors into a map of messages.
    44
    45 assert {:error, changeset} = Accounts.create_user(%{password: "short"})
    46 assert "password is too short" in errors_on(changeset).password
    47 assert %{password: ["password is too short"]} = errors_on(changeset)
    48
    49 """
    50 def errors_on(changeset) do
    51 0 Ecto.Changeset.traverse_errors(changeset, fn {message, opts} ->
    52 0 Regex.replace(~r"%{(\w+)}", message, fn _, key ->
    53 0 opts |> Keyword.get(String.to_existing_atom(key), key) |> to_string()
    54 end)
    55 end)
    56 end
